{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"249"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/249"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.33,0.01,0.07,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26691"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42038"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old woman presents with a six-month history of irregular periods. Usually, she has her period every 28 days, but now they are 40+ days apart. She says she constantly feels hot and flushed. She has been very anxious since the onset of her symptoms, reporting intermittent palpitations that come on at rest and difficulty sleeping. Upon further questioning, she also reports a 10kg weight loss during this timeframe. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no other medical history and does not take any regular medications. She smokes five cigarettes/day and drinks alcohol socially. On examination, her temperature is 36.5C, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, pulse rate 110/min, respiratory rate 15/min and SpO2 97% on room air. She appears diaphoretic. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Her chest is clear on auscultation. Neck examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phaeochromocytoma","Perimenopause","Anxiety","Neuroendocrine tumour (carcinoid syndrome)","Hyperthyroidism"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by increased thyroid hormone synthesis and secretion from the thyroid gland. The most common cause of hyperthyroidism is Grave\u2019s disease which is an autoimmune condition. The characteristic symptoms and signs of hyperthyroidism include palpitations, fatigue, fine tremor, oligomenorrhoea, anxiety, disturbed sleep, weight loss, heat intolerance, sweating and polydipsia.\u00a0\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptoms and signs specific to the cause of thyroid disease include ophthalmopathy, dermopathy and acropachy in Graves\u2019 disease; dysphagia or orthopnoea in nodular goitre and anterior neck pain in subacute thyroiditis. Diagnosis of hyperthyroidism relies initially on measurement of thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH). If reduced, then serum-free T4 and free or total T3 should be measured. Treatment of hyperthyroidism depends on the aetiology, but in general, the three main options are antithyroid drugs, radioactive iodine ablation and surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerimenopause \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be considered, as it commonly presents with irregular periods, hot flushes, and sleep disturbances. However, the patient\u0027s weight loss is a red flag symptom, and along with their other symptoms and tachycardia on examination, makes hyperthyroidism more likely. Moreover, weight gain, not weight loss, is typically seen in perimenopause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile\u003Cstrong\u003E phaeochromocytoma \u003C/strong\u003Eclassically presents with sweating and palpitations, a headache and high blood pressure would also be seen. It would not typically present with irregular periods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnxiety\u003C/strong\u003E is also a valid differential for this patient, however, there is no mention of psychosocial stressors and her anxiety commenced at a similar time to the rest of her symptoms, thus an organic cause must be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoid syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Etypically presents with flushing and chronic diarrhoea. It is the result of the secretion of serotonin and other vasoactive substances into the systemic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["There are several key symptoms to hyperthyroidism including weight loss, sweating, oligomenorrhoea and tremor"],"references":["De Leo S, Lee SY, Braverman LE. Hyperthyroidism. Lancet. 2016;388(10047):906-18.","Sharma A, Stan MN. Thyrotoxicosis: Diagnosis and Management Mayo Clin Proc. 2019; 94:1048-64"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26691"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"249"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26691"},"attributes":{"